race: Illness (CFS), had no training the entire year.
Run about 2/3 and walked about 1/3 of the distance.
Low electrolyte intake caused cramping.
Around 13 gels ~200kcal (~2600kcal) each and some with caffeine.
Barely finished in time.
Feet blistered, barely walking, 1 month to recover just walking.
event: Lots of running by the coast so exposed to the sun and heat.
I don't recall but I think the aid stations were decent. I recall water, and maybe gels and soda.
Don't recall if there was a finishing refreshments bag but they definitely offered ice cream (magnum?).
takeaways: Train.
Take more electrolytes.
Decrease gels.

race: Had about 6 weeks training until health crashed for the next 6 weeks prior to event.
Fueled every 45m: total 5 gels ~450kcal, 5 electrolyte sticks: sodium ~1200g, 250g potassium.
Some preworkout before and during race.
Increased electrolytes significantly helped performance.
Run almost the entire distance, but slowly with some walking at the end.
Had about 2 oranges, 2 bananas from stations, and water with juice/soda was needed too.
Quick partial recovery, felt ok within 1 week but need more time.
After 2 weeks I could probably attempt another event since no injuries this time but needed < 3 weeks.
event: Run through the city and some green areas which had a bit of shade and incline.
Don't recall the finishing refreshment bag but I threw away almost all of it.
takeaways: Need to increase electrolytes and gels.

race: Mostly observed recovery from previous event so not much training, 1 1/2 marathon + misc.
Carb loaded with low quality pasta and minced beef, avoid, was constipated during race because of this type of meat.
Slept under 5h, felt heavy and unwell because of the meat but not sick, I knew the race would be difficult and sluggish.
Had preworkout before race and in drink.
Took sodium ~200g, potassium ~300g before race, added 1.5x to drink during race.
Got up at 04:30 like in Lisbon, I prefer starting at 09:00
Fueled every 45m, total 8 gels ~730kcal, 5 electrolyte sticks: sodium ~1200g, 250g potassium.
Ate half a banana, half an orange during race, maybe 3 bottles of blue gatorade + water.
It was hot and sunny so I got a little sunburnt. It drained my energy and I was really slow.
Stopped to walk so many times and yet my time was faster than in Split, Croatia where I felt much better.
All the gels and extra electrolytes helped but calves started to cramp a little after 31km.
Wasted 10 minutes on 2 bathroom breaks so I could have been faster, also 2 minutes waiting after the start of the race.
Because of the heat I thought I wouldn't finish or have a much worse time.
Feet have some blood blisters but I can walk after the race.
event: Sunny, cloudless, exposed route mostly in underdeveloped areas.
Running some of the route by the ocean without much wind so the heat is pretty bad.
Don't recall the finishing refreshment bag but I threw away most of it.
takeaways: Buy sunscreen next time.
Buy an anti-chafe product.
Don't carb load as much. Overdid it this time.

race: For the last 2 weeks I've focused on recovery so I didn't exercise at all (although I could).
Haven't been sleeping well, taking naps during the day.
Waking up multiple times per hour the night before event so didn't sleep much but I didn't feel obviously sleep deprived.
Generally lower energy all the way up to event.
Walked < 10km day before event. Should have put on sunscreen.
Didn't overeat/carb load like last time, larger portions than regular meals but much less overall.
Had preworkout before race and in drink.
Took sodium ~200g, potassium ~300g before race, added same amount to drink for race.
Will use sunscreen and anti-chafe, especially on feet.
Running to event was difficult enough (only 2km) - CFS.
Fueled every 45m, total 8 gels ~860kcal, 5 electrolyte sticks: sodium ~1200g, 250g potassium.
Many half cups of isotonic liquid and maybe 1L of water.
Didn't have the energy because of CFS and the sun was draining despite using sunscreen.
Very slow running, waddling from side to side with a bunch of walking.
Because of CFS and the sun I started taking breaks from 18km while usually I last till around 23-24km before I need to walk a bit.
Severly dehydrated despite drinking a lot. Started mild cramping around that time till the end.
Feet are a little blistered, not bad, product helped a little.
Can waddle around slowly. Overall not too bad given the dehydration.
event: They started at 08:30 but staggered the runners so they made me wait for 24m before starting.
Aid stations were inconsistent and not great.
Served water, isotonic liquids and apples.
Big city, lots of people in certain areas. Clean city, good vibes.
Bunch of runners needed first aid, even just before the finish line - heatstroke?
It was hot and sunny with little shade / protection.
Best medal so far but finishing bag of refreshments was meh. Only kept the drinks.
takeaways: Need to purchase breathable, long sleeved, white top for more sun protection.
May need to increase electrolyte even more especially for sunny climates.
May need to drink more and risk toilet breaks - didn't use it once this time despite drinking a lot.
May need an additional sugary/sweet drink in case aid stations don't have any.
Carb load more, could have eaten a bit more. Was a bit hungry the day before. 500g of pasta wasn't enough.
Start to drink frequently from the start e.g. every 20m.

race: Lots of travel to get to the island, feel kinda meh.
Kinda carb loading but with pancakes, jam, chocolate and biscuits, sodas, with a bit of regular spaghetti and meat.
Will wear sunscreen and a light colored long sleeved t-shirt. I'm unsure about the material providing sun protection because of how thin it is.
Using a new anti-chafe cream I randomly picked up at Decathlon.
Had some time to train so I run a few 10 milers and some high intensity intervals, hoping it helps.
Carb loaded a bit too much with simple sugars so I only consumed 5+1 gels.
Felt like I may vomit because of the carbs for most of the run.
Started fueling from 30m intervals and pushed it up to an hour or more to not vomit.
No cramps at all, 5 electrolyte sticks: sodium ~1200g, 250g potassium.
Almost completely exposed to the sun the entire time but the sunscreen and long sleeve helped significantly.
I didn't notice when it started but I should have been drinking more. Towards the latter half I was borderline dehydrated and at one point I run out of water and could have gotten heatstroke.

I saw the elevation before but had no real life reference. From the beginning it was basically a mountain run on a road. I practically gave up on a faster time at the start and just wanted to finish. After that massive climb there were many inclines and declines so I walked up and tried to run down / straight most of the time. I trained for flat, not mountains.
Went the wrong way once, almost got lost. Only lost a few minutes.
Some parts were very easy and others were difficult and really sucked.
First time using new watch and it gave me some trouble early on which really frustrated me but now I know what it does and how to use it there.
Finished pretty strong, barely any stops for the last few miles after I got some water.
No issues with the bulky chip.
Training definitely helped. I ache but don't feel exhausted. Didn't need to sit down right after but if it wasn't so hot and sunny and there was a place to sit I may have done so.
Almost no friction burns this time because of the cream. I was dehydrated which is when I've noticed it started to rub a bit but pretty good, just needed to stay hydrated.

Feet are a little beaten up and there's minor swelling. Minor blood blisters under some toenails. A few days later I cut the nails and a blister by accident which got infected and I needed to take antibiotics for 1 week.
event: On an island, by the coast, completely exposed to the sun.
Big mountain and lots of elevation change on road.
Small marathon so the chip is a thick box on the bib unlike the usual small thin line.
I don't recall seeing a single toilet on the route, perhaps I've missed it.
Roads were mostly closed but some cars drive by.
Small island where you run on a road by the coast so not many people except the runners or aid stations, even when running through towns.
Markings and aid stations were fine, mostly had liquids but towards the end some had fruits.
There were seemingly no zones at the start. People just crammed themselves in the small road, anywhere, at the start.
The island is a pain to get to. Flights, trains, ferries and taxis.It could take 7h to get to the start from Florence.
No refreshment pack at the end?
takeaways: Simple sugars are fine but even if you feel fine you may not feel ok when running, especially when fueling. Give yourself more time to slowly carb load over a few days with heavier meals.

Improved perception for thirst by touching the palms but need to drink more when the sun is cooking you. Liquids were better but still not enough. If it wasn't for the sugar bomb and potentially vomitting increasing water would have helped a lot.
Drank every 15-30m plus aid stations but need more liquids with easy access to drink a little and more often.

race: Not much time to train plus I was travelling so only did a handful or runs since the last event.
Been on lots of antibiotics for a few weeks partially because of wisdom tooth removal, including 5 days before this event.
Energy felt low for a couple weeks up until event. Excitement must have boosted my energy just before.
Did a mix of simple carb loading the day before (waffles with chocolate and jam, some biscuits with chocolate) and regular carb loading with pasta etc.
Standard fueling, 7 gels ~30m, 2x 500ml bottles with preworkout and electrolytes that I've been sipping every few minutes.

Run out of my liquids in the last few miles but kept using aid stations throughout. I didn't feel like I needed/could take more liquid but towards the end I was slightly dehydrated and definitely needed it when I run out.
First marathon that I run the whole way, no stops for walking except when zigzagging around people at the aid station for water.
Started cramping pretty badly towards the end so significantly slowed down, almost had to stop a few times but the cramps resolved themselves enough to speed up again.

It was warm, I think around the same temperature as most other marathons but this had a little wind, lots of water sprinklers which I avoided and lots of shade from buildings so I wasn't burning in the direct sun the whole time. I didn't really feel that hot.
24000 runners so lots of annoying zigzagging around walls of people.
New running vest really helped with the water and fuel access.
Didn't really feel sick but a few times it felt like some water was coming up so I thought I shouldn't drink as much.
Needed water, when I sat down later I had a massive calf cramp.
No blisters or friction burns, just a bit sore, needed to sit down and rest.
Walking around things are generally fine the day after but sleep has suffered immediately after.
event: Lots of runners so we had to line up from outside the venue to pick up the bibs.
Expo sucked, not much to look at.

We were funnelled to the starting zones by groups from the same area we got bibs. Walking for a bit to get there with lots of toilets at each zone. I was surprised at how well organised the start was.
Aid stations were good too, usually water with some having coke and maybe redbull, fruits, gels, lots of people helping.
Beautiful city, enough shade, lots of people.

I've been avoiding the sprinklers because I didn't want to get wet but at mile 19 some old cunt with a hose blasted all the runners, including me, and I had a bunch of money on me, it seems to have dried.

The ending was ~0.5km longer than it should have been, that's pretty bad, plus they funnelled us into a stadium to finish where there was only 1 small way out so lots of people had to stand there right after the finish line shuffling foward for maybe 10+ minutes just to make it out. That was just stupid and frustrating.
They only gave a carton of water after the medal so no refreshments at the end. I usually throw it out anyway.
Really nice medal but the stap looks like cheap, old shit. The discrepancy is large. If this had a decent strap it would probably be my favourite in terms of quality.
takeaways: I think I had a hydration issue because of the cramps but I'm unsure if I needed to take even more water throughout or more electrolytes.

Also unsure if I should try to take more gels in the future since slowing down that much might not just be a hydration/undertraining issue but at the same time I didn't feel like I needed gels desperately and didn't even use the last one.

race: Training volume has increased to a peak of < 40 miles per week.
Trained on inclines.
Mix of simple and complex sugars (carbs) before event, no nausea.
Used carb mix (20g iirc) in liquids with electrolytes and preworkout.
First half was relatively easy and fun but some parts were very hilly.
Second half was almost entirely up mountains, it was very steep for a long time, repeatedly.
Altitude wasn't really an issue at this level since my HR was lower than expected but I couldn't run up the hills for long.
Most of the 2nd half was walking up hills, on a few occasions I had to use my hands to help me up.
I was decently hydrated but got surface level cramps at times.
I should have brought a little more electrolyte sticks, 1 or 2 more.
The ISO drinks at the stations helped a lot.
Brought 10 gels, forgot I had 1 which would have helped but that's a lot of carbs over time. I think I would have been fine to take it but I need something else.
At the ultra section I was stopped for a mandatory safety check < 5mins.
At the ultra I was barely walking, low energy and tired but I never stopped despite the mountains.
On a few occasions I could have fallen down the mountain, with the amount of rocks and incline that could have been death.
The sun was burning, I have pretty bad sunburn in areas I've not applied sunscreen. The heat itself was manageable.
About 1/6 did not finish the ultra and 1/5 the marathon.
No friction burns and only minor blisters, almost none.
Felt fine, a few days rest and I'll be back to training.
event: Beautiful scenery.
They altered the course slightly because of weather.
Aid stations were good, lots of liquids, some bananas and gels.
They gave the same medal to ultra and marathon finishers which is very disappointing, and the medal is kinda meh.
Refreshments at the end was meh, I gave it to others.
The bib contained a ticket for public transport so I could travel for free.
takeaways: Need electrolytes tablets to drop into water.
Need to figure out ultra nutrition because gels are too sweet after a while.

race: Run 100 miles in 1 week as a challange and been training for pace more than distance closer to the event.
It's been hot so it's been difficult to run even in the gym at the treadmill.
It's windy and coldish in Iceland so after travelling I crashed and slept well for the first time in as far as I remember.
Pre-race sleep was back to meh as usual.
Stomach was a bit off and I felt slightly above average, I didn't feel like I really had the energy to run hard.
A bit cold but really windy. It was difficult to run against the wind at times it was so strong.
Took 6 40g carb gels and felt fine. Was a bit hungry before and at the start despite stuffing myself with carbs before.
Since it was windy and cool I didn't drink much but I was aware of it so I kept trying to take sips of electrolytes to prevent fatigue and cramps.
Maintained a decent pace up to around mile 20 where I slightly slowed because of cramp worries and muscle fatigue (need to run more).
Usually I start to drop off around 14-16 miles so gels and training helped.
If it wasn't for the borderline cramping I would have pushed a bit harder, my heart rate was surprisingly low for most of it so I could have pushed more.
Generally fine, bit tired, knees a bit questionable but seem fine.
Walked a bunch of miles after getting food and shopping a bit so I'm ok.

I wasn't really clothed appropriately especially towards the end when it started to rain a bit so I was cold and I'm anticipating a cold and decreased everything over the next few weeks but we'll see.
event: Poor organisation. Despite knowning when we should start it was a clusterfuck with a mistimed start. Doesn't really matter since what matters is when your bib tracker crosses the start and end lines, still annoying.
Barely any distance markers but they did have a bunch of boards and volunteers to point the way.
Medal is pretty and there was no refreshments bag at the end but they had a bunch of tables with so many treats and drinks which was really nice.
The marathon itself is only slightly longer than the actual distance and it's meh, nothing spectacular to look at.
When it started raining all the supporters vanished at the end which was amusing and disgusting. I'm trying not to die and you're all warm and terrified of the rain?
takeaways: Iceland is expensive. Do not go shopping here or eat out.

Really surprised at stomach taking that many carbs on top of all the carb loading. I did slow towards the end so maybe I could squeeze in 1 more gel but really it was mostly cramp management so need more electrolytes and maybe liquids (although I did need to urinate so maybe not liquid).
Salt pills crumble and make a bit of a mess, maybe bring extra or different product.

race: Not many workouts since Iceland, mostly recovering.
Did not get sick at all but despite not feeling particularly weakened I was not sufficiently recovered to run the event.
From the start my legs felt overworked and heart rate shot right up.
Body was disregulated. Started at a faster Iceland pace and felt natural except the legs and heart, quickly slowed after that.
Bit of contrasting weather, clear skies weren't hot but running in shaded woodlands dropped the temp drastically. Running in sweaty clothes with cold winds is unpleasant.
Hills were very difficult in some sections, lots of walking there.
Fueling was fine but was cramping at times and ended up walking a lot of the event because muscle fibers in legs were overworked. I was not ready since the PB in Iceland.
Waddling along, not so much tired but seriously overworked, fortunately did not get injured.
event: Beautiful area, from the start to villages to the mountains
Very well marked, stationed and organised.
They gave coupons for travel to and from the location plus the BIB supposedly had free local transport. The coupons saved me ~ 150 CHF.
BIB pickup came with a large delicious swiss milk chocolate bar.
Medal is small and not very interesting.
No refreshments bag at the end but they gave out isotonic bottles and people could get beer for some reason.
Free and prioritised gondola ride down the mountain.
takeaways: 2 weeks is not enough of recovery after setting a significant PB in another event
I must run more consistently to adapt otherwise I will keep cramping and feeling overworked -> slow down.

race: Everything was humid and wet from the start line, running in shin deep water through flooded paths with large vertical falls right next to you.
Mountains were flooded so you could literally sit and slide down long sections - or slip.
event: Thunderstorm for days before event caused the route to be altered and then during the race the remaining route would have taken us through a path that was shin deep in water but the storm made it neck high therefore it was too dangerous to cross and the event was cancelled.
Had to return by foot down the mountain through unmarked paths for many kilometers which was easy to get lost.
They expected weather conditions to change but were unprepared, overall bad organisation.
4 months after the event I still haven't received any email for a coupon code to sign up for the next event and it looks like some updates have been made on the site for next year.
Highly mountainous but not technical at least the start.

race: Overtrained and didn't feel recovered with a 1 week break before event.
Ate more than normal but wasn't properly carb loading. Should have ate a lot more carbs.
Wanted to PB so was nervous and a bit excited for the first time in forever.
Stomach wasn't ideal but had no issues during the event.
Running faster than usual marathon pace so given insufficient carb loading and recovery even the half way point was more difficult than normal.
Last 10 miles were a grind, especially the last few when I slowed down.
Averaged ~120g of carbs/gels per hour which is significantly more than I've taken.
Literally couldn't keep taking gels towards the end, had to run holding half a gel and finish it a bit later.
Didn't take in enough water so minor cramping in left knee.
Venice islands were a bit flooded, ankle deep which wasn't pleasant.
Walking was difficult after. No blisters or foot issues. Quads and upper thighs are still sore 3 days later.
Wasn't really hungry or thirsty which is a bit weird but given the number of gels it's understandable.
Some friction burn around groin.
event: Busses to start line was an hour earlier than it should be so everyone waited for 90 minutes outside in a field with cool weather, wearing bin bags etc. to stay warm.
Nothing to look at except the last couple miles when you're on the Venice islands.
Stations used water bottles which is great because you can take it and fill up your bottles with electrolytes as you run.
Start zones were weird, slower pacers started way to far into the middle creating walls and somehow my zone was behind them when I was much faster.
takeaways: Running more helped but needed more time/gadgets to recover.

race: No training for 2 weeks since Venice.
Been comfort eating so got a bit fatter.
Carb loaded on potatoes only and some confectionaries.
Injured leg crossing into start line but after a few miles I was limp/running for ~20 miles (slowly)
Felt pretty good at first but bloating caused a bathroom break with thoughts of many more, struggled taking gels and took none for the last hour.
event: Except that stupid rope we had to step over and the couple hundred meters to find the medal it was well organised.
They didn't give water bottles and instead cups of liquids like usual which is not good because you have to slow down to drink or fill up, can't fill up own bottles when needed.
Pretty views by the oceans and massive and colorful medal, may be the prettiest of all this year.
takeaways: 2 weeks recovery after a tough PB is not enough. Needed at least 2 more weeks to just start training again.
First few miles had decent pace so without bloating, leg, and 2 weeks of no training I think I could have had a chance to PB again especially given my recovery time.

race: Only a few training sessions since Nice because of travel.
Carb loading on lasagna + pizza = no GI issues.
Zero degree weather but not much wind.
10 miles on pace and then started to slow down because of lack of training - felt more difficult than I'd like but fine overall.
Strange temporary post-race-meal leg injury that went away later.
Could walk and run a bit later in the day, run 10 miles slightly under marathon pace 2 days later which ended up being too much and exhausting for a few days.
Malaise and naps for the next week.
event: Everything was just fine. Nothing to really look at. Prettiest medal of the year.
takeaways: Need to train more.

race: Messed up meds a few weeks ago still having an impact so barely any training since Florence.
Woke up depleted, empty without energy expecting a bad run.
1 minute slower per mile and it got worse.
event: Decent organisation, mainly using bottles of water instead of cups.
Expo was a pain, small with thousands of people cramped.
Medal is a bit smaller than usual and it has some stupid fish design but it spins in the middle. May break one day.
takeaways: Need to train more.

race: Bad sleep, sinus and GI issues because of protein bars during event.
Unable to fuel because of GI, had 2 emergency stops in the woods and so was only able to hike most of the event.
Went off course many times - extra 3km + 100m ascent.
Strong freezing winds - dangerously shivered after event when trying to return.
event: Highly technical at times, gotta be careful, otherwise can run most of it except the steep mountains.
Lots of liquids and mini snacks but not many aid stations specifically like 10 miles between each toilet..
Most of the time you're in the wilderness away from civilization by many miles, don't die.
Probably best to stay in hotel right next to start but groceries and train station are awkward in the village - can stay in city instead but need shuttle to event.
Race was altered from 55km to 59km and they added 4h. With stomach issues, unaltered, I would have DNF'd on time checkpoints.
takeaways: Do not eat protein bars during and reduce protein days before event to clear out intestines, stick to gels / simple carbs when running and pasta/potatoes.
Gotta try bringing meds for stomach just in case because I will DNF at some point.
Friction cream was surprisingly good for like 10 miles at a time but likely because of weather, need to try other products.

race: Took ~80g/h of gels/carbs and at the halfway point I felt a little underfueled.
Cramped towards the halfway point because of insufficient liquid/electrolyte intake.
After a 10+ minute aid station stop/prep at the halfway point I felt ready to finsh the 2nd half.
No digestive issues when only taking gels.
event: Very well organised.
First kit check for everyone at the start.
Nice routes, some of the climbs/drops required you to stop and use hands and feet with volunteers helping you for safety.
Overall not very technical but don't slip and fall down the mountain to almost certain death
All events were cancelled partway due to intense winds in the mountains and fire risks.
takeaways: 80g/h is okay but either need to take an extra gel every ~4h or increase per hour intake.
Gotta come back for a longer distance than 51km.
Alicante airport -> bus to main bus station -> 2h bus to Alcoy, infrequent buses so pain to travel to but nice towns.
Vaseline was good but needed to reapply at the halfway point aid station, should have done it earlier to reduce the few small blisters.
